{"key":"post-9103835","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9103835</id>\n<content>Potting soils were commonly used as casing material ten to twenty years ago.&amp;nbsp; However, peat-verm is and always has been superior to potting soils.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, casing mix and bulk substrates should be &lt;i&gt;pasteurized&lt;/i&gt;, not sterilized.&amp;nbsp; &lt;i&gt;Pasteurization involves heating pre-moistened, field capacity material to 140F to 160F (60c to 70c) for one hour.&lt;/i&gt;&amp;nbsp; Super-heating in the microwave is partial sterilization, which makes it more prone to contaminants, not less.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9104911</next>\n<prev>9103479</prev>\n<first>6789654</first>\n<last>9106781</last>\n<when>1224524509</when>\n<utime>10/20/08 08:41 PM</utime>\n</post>"}